09115nam a22011655i 9789814762281DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162016si     fo  d z      eng d  a2017344004  a97898147622817 a10.1355/97898147622812doi  a(DE-B1597)491753  a(OCoLC)1011183257  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG00aHC412b.M35 2016 4aHC412bM364 2016 7aBUS0690002bisacsh04a338.9522300aManaging Globalization in the Asian Century :bEssays in Honour of Prema-Chandra Athukorala /ced. by Hal Hill, Jayant Menon. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (556 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables -- tFigures -- tContributors -- t1. Introduction -- tPART 1. SPECIAL TOPICS -- t2. ACGE Decomposition Approach to Identifying the Effects of Trade Reform: NAFTA and the U.S. Economy Between 1992 and 1998 -- t3. Economic Analysis versus Business Rent-seeking: The Eclipse of Analysis in Australia -- t4. Growth Slowdown and the Middle Income Trap in Asia -- t5. Workers’ Remittances, Capital Inflows, and Economic Growth in Developing Asia and the Pacific Countries -- t6. Development in Southeast Asia’s Lagging Regions -- t7. A Comparative Study of Global Production Sharing in the Automotive Industry in China and India -- t8. La Pesadilla Neoliberal: Why East Asia Did Not Experience a “Neo-liberal Nightmare” While Latin America Did? -- t9. Housing Prices, Graduates, and Income Inequality: The Case of Singapore -- t10. The Role of Trade in Fostering Inclusive Growth in the Asia-Pacific -- t11. The TPP Unveiled: The Good, the Bad, and the Ugly -- tPART 2. COUNTRY STUDIES -- t12. The Japanese Macroeconomic Mystery -- t13. Myanmar’s Opening to the World Economy -- t14. Trade Policy and Industrialization in India Since the 1991 Reforms -- t15. Policies toward Globalization in Sri Lanka, 1960–2012: Change and Continuity -- t16. The Political Economy of the Rajapaksa Decade in Sri Lanka, 2005–14: Policy Contradictions and Mal-governance -- t17. Has Indonesia Passed the Lewis Turning Point and Does It Matter? -- t18. Half a Century of Indonesian Economic Development: Continuity and Change -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe global centre of gravity continues to shift to the Asia-Pacific, the most dynamic region in the world. These economies have generally grown faster for longer periods of time than any other major region in world history. Their embrace of globalization has been a central feature, and driver, of their dynamism. The management of Asia-Pacific economic integration and globalization is crucial not only for the countries themselves but also for the state of the global economy, including importantly latecomer developing economies who look to the region for analytical and development policy lessons. Twenty-eight leading international authorities in the field, drawn from nine countries, provide a comprehensive examination of the causes, consequences and challenges of globalization, in a volume that celebrates the distinguished career of Professor Prema-Chandra Athukorala. Among the major issues examined are the region’s distinctive approach to trade liberalization, the effects of economic growth on poverty reduction and the labour market, the special challenges of by-passed regions, the role of ideas in influencing policy making, the modalities of connecting to global production networks, and the importance of remittances in economic development. Several country case studies provide in-depth analyses of development processes and outcomes. These include episodes in economic development, the challenges faced by transition economies, the macroeconomics of adjusting to slower growth and rising debt in advanced economies, and the so-called middle-income trap phenomenon.  aMode of access: Interne